{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:48","names":{"en":"Mahdid","tr":"Mehdîler","ar":"al-Mahdiyyūn"},"country":["SA","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1159,"extinct":1173},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"48","atlas_name_en_original":"The Mahdids","parent_tribe":"Ru'aynî/Himyerî (Tubba' soyundan iddia)","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Güney Arap)","capital":"Zebîd","region_primary":"Yemen (Zebîd ve Tihâme)","regions_all":"Zebîd; Tihâme; Ta'iz (geçici); Aden (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Necâhîler","successor":"Eyyûbîler","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Mahdids were a militant Yemeni dynasty that overthrew the Najahids through a radical preaching movement and established short-lived rule in Zabid. The Ayyubid conquest ended their rapid rise and fall with equal speed.","importance_level":"Düşük","capital_lat":"14.2","capital_lon":"43.32","century_start":12,"century_end":12}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:44","names":{"en":"Najāhid","tr":"Necâhîler","ar":"al-Najāhiyyūn"},"country":["SA","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1022,"extinct":1158},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"44","atlas_name_en_original":"The Najāhids","parent_tribe":"Habeşli (Habashi) köle kökenli","ethnic_origin":"Habeş (Etiyopyalı)","capital":"Zebîd","region_primary":"Yemen (Tihâme)","regions_all":"Zebîd; Tihâme","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Ziyâdîler (köle vezirleri)","successor":"Mehdîler (554/1159)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Najahids were a rare Islamic dynasty of Ethiopian origin, emerging from Ziyadid slave viziers to establish an independent dynasty centered in Zabid in the Tihama. The rise of a Black African slave family to the ruling class in the Islamic world is a remarkable example of social mobility.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"14.2","capital_lon":"43.32","century_start":11,"century_end":12}}
{"id":"Q1190581","names":{"en":"Rasulid dynasty","tr":"Resûlîler","ar":"al-Rasūliyyūn"},"country":["SA","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1228,"extinct":1454},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"49","atlas_name_en_original":"The Rasūlids","parent_tribe":"Oğuz Türk (Mencik boyu, Gassânî soy iddiası)","ethnic_origin":"Türk (Oğuz)","capital":"Ta'iz","region_primary":"Güney Yemen ve Tihâme","regions_all":"Ta'iz; Zebîd; San'a (geçici); Hadramevt; Zufâr","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Eyyûbîler (Yemen kolu)","successor":"Tâhirîler","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Sünnî","narrative_en":"The Rasulids were a dynasty of Turkic origin that inherited the Ayyubid Yemeni legacy, ruling southern Yemen and the Tihama for 230 years and building the region's cultural golden age. They accumulated immense wealth by controlling trade with India, China, and East Africa through the port of Aden. Sultans personally authoring scholarly works created a unique intellectual legacy in the Islamic ruler tradition.","importance_level":"Yüksek","capital_lat":"13.58","capital_lon":"44.02","century_start":13,"century_end":15}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:45","names":{"en":"Sulayhid","tr":"Süleyhîler","ar":"al-Sulayhiyyūn"},"country":["SA","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1047,"extinct":1138},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"45","atlas_name_en_original":"The Sulayhids","parent_tribe":"Hemdân kabilesi","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Güney Arap)","capital":"San'a; Dhū Cibla (geç dönem)","region_primary":"Yemen (San'a → Dhū Cibla)","regions_all":"San'a; Dhū Cibla; Tihâme; Hicaz (geçici); Aden (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Zeydî İmamlar (San'a'da)","successor":"Zürey'îler (Aden)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Şiî","narrative_en":"The Sulayhids rose as the most successful representatives of the Fatimid Ismaili mission in Yemen, presenting one of Islamic history's most remarkable examples of female governance through al-Sayyida Arwa, nicknamed the 'Second Bilqis.' They laid the foundations for the lasting influence of Ismaili Shiism in Yemen.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"15.35","capital_lon":"44.21","century_start":11,"century_end":12}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:50","names":{"en":"Tāhirid","tr":"Tâhirîler","ar":"al-Tāhiriyyūn"},"country":["SA","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1454,"extinct":1517},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"50","atlas_name_en_original":"The Tāhirids","parent_tribe":"Yerli Yemenli Sünnî aile","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Güney Arap)","capital":"al-Mikrâne (al-Miqrāna); Cubân (Juban)","region_primary":"Güney Yemen ve Tihâme","regions_all":"Aden; Zebîd; San'a (geçici); Ta'iz","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Resûlîler","successor":"Mısır Memlûk/Osmanlı fethi","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Tahirids were southern Yemeni emirs who gained power as the Rasulid state weakened, defending Aden against the Portuguese threat and representing the region's last independent local dynasty.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"13.8","capital_lon":"44.12","century_start":15,"century_end":16}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:43","names":{"en":"Yu'firid","tr":"Yu'firîler (Ya'furîler)","ar":"al-Yu'firiyyūn"},"country":["SA","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":847,"extinct":997},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"43","atlas_name_en_original":"The Yu'firids or Ya'furids","parent_tribe":"Himyerî (eski Tubba' kralları soyundan iddia)","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Güney Arap)","capital":"San'a; Cenad","region_primary":"Yemen yayla bölgesi","regions_all":"San'a; Cenad (Janad)","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Abbâsî valileri","successor":"Küçük yerel beyler","government_type":"İmamet","religious_orientation":"Şiî","narrative_en":"The Yu'firids were the first local South Arabian dynasty based in Sana'a, ruling the Yemeni highlands before the Sulayhids. While maintaining Abbasid allegiance, they provided regional stability, representing an early political expression of Yemeni highland culture.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"15.35","capital_lon":"44.21","century_start":9,"century_end":10}}
{"id":"Q726509","names":{"en":"Zaydi Imams","tr":"Yemen Zeydî İmamları","ar":"al-A'imma al-Zaydiyya fī al-Yaman"},"country":["SA","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":897,"extinct":1962},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"41","atlas_name_en_original":"The Zaydī Imāms of Yemen","parent_tribe":"Hasanî Şerifler (Rassî kolu)","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Şerif/Hasanî)","capital":"Sa'de; San'a (değişen)","region_primary":"Yüksek Yemen (Sa'de ve San'a)","regions_all":"Sa'de; San'a; Yemen yayla bölgesi","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":null,"successor":"Yemen Arap Cumhuriyeti (1962 darbesi; 1970 cumhuriyet)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Şiî","narrative_en":"The Zaidi Imams of Yemen constituted one of the longest-lived political structures in the Islamic world with an imamate tradition spanning over a millennium. Resisting Sunni and Ismaili rivals in the mountainous geography of Highland Yemen, the Zaidi imams shaped the region's sectarian identity by preserving a distinctive model of moderate Shiism.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"16.94","capital_lon":"43.76","century_start":9,"century_end":20}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:42","names":{"en":"Ziyādid","tr":"Ziyâdîler","ar":"al-Ziyādiyyūn"},"country":["SA","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":818,"extinct":1018},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"42","atlas_name_en_original":"The Ziyādids","parent_tribe":"Ziyâd b. Ebîhi soyundan (iddia)","ethnic_origin":"Arap","capital":"Zebîd (Zabīd)","region_primary":"Yemen (Tihâme)","regions_all":"Zebîd; Tihâme; Hadramevt (kısmen)","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Abbâsî valileri","successor":"Necâhîler (Habeşli köle vezirleri)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Ziyadids were Yemen's first major local dynasty, founded by a governor sent by the Abbasid caliph, ruling from the Tihama center of Zabid for two centuries. In their later period, power passed to Ethiopian slave viziers, creating an early example of social mobility in Yemeni history.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"14.2","capital_lon":"43.32","century_start":9,"century_end":11}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:46","names":{"en":"Zuray'id","tr":"Zürey'îler (Benü'l-Kerem)","ar":"al-Zuray'iyyūn / Banū al-Karam"},"country":["SA","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1080,"extinct":1175},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"46","atlas_name_en_original":"The Zuray'ids or Banū 'l-Karam","parent_tribe":"Cüşem / Benû Yâm","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Güney Arap)","capital":"Aden","region_primary":"Güney Yemen (Aden)","regions_all":"Aden ve çevresi","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Süleyhîler (Aden'de)","successor":"Eyyûbîler (571/1175 fethi)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Zuray'ids governed the Aden branch of the Sulayhid state, controlling the strategic transit point of international maritime trade as a small but wealthy dynasty. Internal warfare and the growing influence of Ethiopian slave viziers weakened the dynasty, paving the way for the Ayyubid conquest.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"12.79","capital_lon":"45.03","century_start":11,"century_end":12}}
